{"title_page": "Obstructing the field", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n'''Obstructing the field''' is one of the nine methods of [[dismissal (cricket)|dismissing]] a [[batsman]] in the sport of [[cricket]]. It dictates that either batsman can be given out if he wilfully attempts to obstruct or distract the [[Fielding (cricket)|fielding side]] by word or action. It is governed by Law 37 of the [[laws of cricket]], and is a rare way for a batsman to be dismissed; in the history of cricket, there has been only one instance in [[Test cricket|Test matches]], six occasions in [[One Day International]] (ODI) games, and only one instance in [[Twenty20]] International matches. However, there have also been seven instances in Test cricket, and two in ODIs, where a batsman has been dismissed [[handled the ball]], a mode of dismissal now folded into obstructing the field. In most cases an obstruction occurs when a batsman thinks that he is going to be [[Run out (cricket)|run out]] and he blocks the ball with his bat or changes his course while [[running between wickets]] to block the ball. The obstruction has to be deliberate, so a batsman will not be out if the contact with the ball is inadvertent.\n\nThe only time a batsman has been dismissed obstructing the ball in a Test match was during the [[South African cricket team in England in 1951|South African cricket team's tour of England in 1951]] when, in the fifth Test, England's [[Leonard Hutton]] [[Glossary of cricket terms#T|top edged]] the ball and, thinking the ball would hit the stumps, attempted to hit the ball away, thereby preventing the [[wicket-keeper]] from [[Catch (cricket)|catching]] the ball.\n\n==Definition==\nObstructing the field is Law 37 in the [[Laws of cricket]] established by the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC). A batsman can be given out for obstructing the field if he wilfully attempts to obstruct or distract the fielding side by word or action.<ref name=\"mcc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.lords.org/mcc/laws-of-cricket/laws/law-37-obstructing-the-field/ |title=Law 37 \u2013 Obstructing the field |publisher=MCC |accessdate=29 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nLaw 37 describes the following three circumstances where this applies (but the law is not limited to these circumstances):\n*If, in the act of playing the ball, the batsmen wilfully strikes the ball with a hand not holding the bat, unless this is to avoid injury.{{efn|This situation was previously covered in a separate Law:[[Handled the ball]].}}\n\n*If either batsman should wilfully obstruct or distract a fielder preventing a catch being made.\n*If, at any time while the ball is in play and without the consent of a fielder, he uses his bat or any part of his person, to return the ball to any fielder.\nThe latter situation isan is being helpful in returning the ball. A bowler does not receive credit for the wicket when a batsman is dismissed in this fashion, and any runs that have been completed before the offence is committed are scored (unless the obstruction prevents a catch being made{{efn|In this case any penalty runs will stand.<ref name=\"mcc\"/>}}).\n\n==Earliest recorded instance==\nThe first known instance of a player being dismissed in a manner equivalent to the modern term 'Obstructing the field' occurred in a minor match at Sheffield on 27 August 1792, between [[Sheffield Cricket Club]] and Bents Green. The Bents Green player John Shaw, who scored 7 in the first innings, had his dismissal recorded as \"run out of the ground to hinder a catch\". The information was recorded by [[G. B. Buckley]] who found it in the ''Sheffield Advertiser'' dated 31 August 1792. Sheffield won by 10 wickets in a match that was notable for two other reasons, these being that it was the first match played in [[Yorkshire]] for which full scores are recorded and it was the earliest known instance of a three innings match.<ref>Buckley, pp.27\u201328.</ref>\n\n==Dismissals in international cricket==\n===Test cricket===\n[[Len Hutton]] is the only man given out this way in Test cricket, for an incident that occurred at [[The Oval]] during the [[South_African_cricket_team_in_England_in_1951#Fifth_Test|fifth Test]] of South Africa's tour of England in 1951.\n\n===One Day Internationals===\nIn [[One Day International]]s, [[Rameez Raja]] (for Pakistan against England at Karachi in 1987) was given out for hitting the ball away with his bat to avoid being run out going for his century off the last ball of the innings, and [[Mohinder Amarnath]] (for India against Sri Lanka at Ahmedabad in 1989) was given out for kicking the ball away to avoid being run out. Another batsman to be given out this way is [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] of [[Pakistan]] in the first ODI of [[India]] vs [[Pakistan]] Hutch Cup on 6 February 2006. After Inzamam drove the ball to mid off, Indian [[Suresh Raina]] threw it back to the striker's end, Inzamam stopping it with his bat. Umpire [[Simon Taufel]] gave him out as he was in the line of the stumps and out of his crease (and thus would have been run out had the ball hit the stumps).\n\n[[Mohammad Hafeez]] of Pakistan was dismissed obstructing the field on 21 March 2013 in the 4th ODI of the bilateral series match against South Africa. He became the first man to be given out obstructing the field after the new playing conditions were introduced.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/south-africa-v-pakistan-2013/engine/current/match/567371.html]</ref> His teammate, [[Anwar Ali (cricketer born 1987)|Anwar Ali]], was dismissed obstructing the field on 27 November 2013 in the second ODI against South Africa.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/south-africa-v-pakistan-2013-14/content/player/232491.html]</ref>\n\n[[Ben Stokes]] of England was dismissed obstructing the field on 5 September 2015 in the second ODI against Australia for stopping the ball with his hand when the bowler, Mitchell Starc, had thrown the ball in an attempt to run him out.<ref>http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283167.html</ref>\n\nThe complete list of batsmen given out obstructing the field in [[One Day International]]s is:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ One Day International dismissals obstructed the field\n|-\n! No\n! Batsman\n! Country\n! Opposition\n! Venue\n! Match\n! Date\n|-\n|| 1\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Rameez Raja]] \n|| {{cr|PAK}} || {{cr|ENG}} || [[National Stadium|Karachi]], [[Pakistan]] || [[English_cricket_team_in_Pakistan_in_1987\u201388#2nd_ODI|2nd ODI]] || 20 November 1987\n|-\n|| 2 \n! scope=\"row\" | [[Mohinder Amarnath]] \n|| {{cr|IND}} || {{cr|SRI}} || [[Sardar Patel Stadium|Ahmedabad]], [[India]] || [[Nehru Cup (cricket)#India vs Sri Lanka|ODI]] || 22 October 1989\n|-\n|| 3 \n! scope=\"row\" | [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] \n|| {{cr|PAK}} || {{cr|IND}} || [[Arbab Niaz Stadium|Peshawar]], [[Pakistan]] || [[Indian_cricket_team_in_Pakistan_in_2005\u201306#First_ODI|1st ODI]] || 6 February 2006\n|-\n|| 4 \n! scope=\"row\" | [[Mohammad Hafeez]] \n|| {{cr|PAK}} || {{cr|RSA}} || [[Kingsmead Cricket Ground|Durban]], South Africa || [[Pakistani_cricket_team_in_South_Africa_in_2012\u201313#4th_ODI|4th ODI]] || 21 March 2013\n|-\n||5\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Anwar Ali (cricketer born 1987)|Anwar Ali]]\n|| {{cr|PAK}} || {{cr|RSA}} || [[St George's Park Cricket Ground|Port Elizabeth]], South Africa || [[Pakistani_cricket_team_in_South_Africa_in_2013\u201314#2nd_ODI|2nd ODI]] || 27 November 2013\n|-\n||6\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Ben Stokes]]\n|| {{cr|ENG}} || {{cr|AUS}} || [[Lord's]], England || [[Australian_cricket_team_in_England_and_Ireland_in_2015#2nd_ODI|2nd ODI]] || 5 September 2015\n|-\n||7\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Xavier Marshall]]\n|| {{cr|USA}} || {{cr|UAE}} || [[Sharjah Cricket Stadium]], [[Sharjah]] || [[2019 United Arab Emirates Tri-Nation Series#1st_ODI|ODI]] || {{dts|format=dmy|2019|December|8}}\n|}\n\n===Women's One Day Internationals===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ Women's One Day International dismissals obstructed the field\n|-\n! No\n! Batswoman\n! Country\n! Opposition\n! Venue\n! Match\n! Date\n|-\n|| 1\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Thirush Kamini]]\n|| {{crw|IND}} || {{crw|WIN}} || [[ACA\u2013KDCA Cricket Ground|Vijayawada]], India || [[West_Indies_women%27s_cricket_team_in_India_in_2016\u201317#2nd_ODI|2nd ODI]] || 13 November 2016\n|}\n\n===T20 Internationals===\nOn 23 June 2017, in a Twenty20 match against South Africa, [[Jason Roy]] of England was given out obstructing the field, for changing the side of the pitch he was running on when returning from backing up. This caused the returned ball to hit him when he was out of his crease, when it could conceivably have hit the stumps. The South African fielders immediately appealed for a dismissal. Responding to this, the on-field umpires called the ball dead and referred the decision to the third umpire, who gave Roy out.<ref name=\"Roy\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-south-africa-2017/engine/match/1031433.html|title= England vs South Africa T20I scorecard|work=ESPNCricinfo}} </ref>\n\nThe complete list of batsmen given out obstructing the field in [[Twenty20 International]]s is:<ref>{{cite web|title=Records {{!}} Twenty20 Internationals {{!}} Batting records {{!}} Unusual dismissals {{!}} ESPN Cricinfo|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283988.html|website=Cricinfo|accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ T20 International dismissals obstructed the field\n|-\n! No\n! Batsman\n! Country\n! Opposition\n! Venue\n! Match\n! Date\n|-\n|| 1\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Jason Roy]] \n|| {{cr|ENG}} || {{cr|SAF}} || [[County Ground, Taunton|Taunton]], England || [[South_African_cricket_team_in_England_in_2017#2nd_T20I|2nd T20I]] || 23 June 2017\n|-\n|| 2\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Hassan|Rasheed|dab=cricketer}}\n|| {{cr|MDV}} || {{cr|QTR}} || [[Al Amerat Cricket Stadium]], [[Muscat]], Oman || [[2019 ACC Western Region T20#MaldivesQatar|T20I]] ||{{dts|format=dmy|2019|January|23}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Other recent instances==\n[[Mark Ramprakash]] was dismissed obstructing the field on 30 July 2011, in a [[2011 County Championship|County Championship]] Division 2 match between [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] and [[Gloucestershire County Cricket Club|Gloucestershire]]. Ramprakash was deemed to have deliberately tried to distract a fielder who was in the act of trying to run him out. He made no contact with the ball and it did not hit the stumps.<ref name=\"Ramprakash\">BBC, BBC Sport, 30 July 2011, http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/14353907.stm, 31 July 2011</ref>\n\n[[Yusuf Pathan]] of India was dismissed obstructing the field on 15 May 2013 while playing for the Kolkata Knight Riders against the [[Pune Warriors India]] in Match 65 of the 2013 Indian Premier League for deliberately kicking the ball while rotating the strike. He became the first player to be dismissed in T20 cricket in this fashion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wisdenindia.com/cricket-news/yusuf-dismissal-divides-opinion/62480|title=Yusuf dismissal divides opinion|publisher=Wisden India|date=15 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Sheldon Jackson (cricketer)|Sheldon Jackson]] was given out obstructing the field on 3 March 2017 during the [[2016\u201317 Vijay Hazare Trophy]] match against [[Chhattisgarh cricket team|Chhattisgarh]]. Jackson became only the second Indian batsman to be given out in a [[List A cricket|List A match]] in this manner.<ref name=\"Jackson\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/vijay-hazare-trophy-2016-17/content/story/1085065.html |title=Jackson out obstructing the field in Saurashtra's win |accessdate=3 March 2017 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref>\n\n[[Alex Ross]] of the [[Brisbane Heat]] was given out obstructing the field in a [[2017-18 Big Bash League season|Big Bash League]] match against the [[Hobart Hurricanes]] in January 2018 for interfering with an attempted run out. It was the first time in Big Bash League history that a player was given out in this manner.<ref name=\"Ross\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22023835/twitter-reactions-very-very-embarrassing-absolutely-shocking |title='Very very embarrassing! Absolutely shocking'|accessdate=11 January 2018 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref>\n\n[[Ryan Burl]] was given out in a match in the [[2017\u201318 Logan Cup]] by obstructing the field, after he pushed the ball away from the stumps to protect his wicket.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.3-mob.com/sport/logan-cup-burl-hits-century-as-stars-clip-eagles/#.WtsfTH-fiUk |title=Logan Cup: Burl hits century as Stars clip Eagles |work=3-mob.com |accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of unusual dismissals in international cricket]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Buckley |first=G. B. |authorlink=G. B. Buckley |title=Fresh Light on pre-Victorian Cricket |year=1937 |publisher=Cotterell |isbn=}}\n* ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]'' \u2013 various issues\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130311210212/http://www.lords.org/laws-and-spirit/laws-of-cricket/laws/ The official laws of cricket]\n\n{{Methods of dismissal in cricket}}\n\n[[Category:Cricket laws and regulations]]\n[[Category:Cricket terminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n'''Obstructing the field''' is one of the nine methods of [[dismissal (cricket)|dismissing]] a [[batsman]] in the sport of [[cricket]]. It dictates that either batsman can be given out if he wilfully attempts to obstruct or distract the [[Fielding (cricket)|fielding side]] by word or action. It is governed by Law 37 of the [[laws of cricket]], and is a rare way for a batsman to be dismissed; in the history of cricket, there has been only one instance in [[Test cricket|Test matches]], six occasions in [[One Day International]] (ODI) games, and only one instance in [[Twenty20]] International matches. However, there have also been seven instances in Test cricket, and two in ODIs, where a batsman has been dismissed [[handled the ball]], a mode of dismissal now folded into obstructing the field. In most cases an obstruction occurs when a batsman thinks that he is going to be [[Run out (cricket)|run out]] and he blocks the ball with his bat or changes his course while [[running between wickets]] to block the ball. The obstruction has to be deliberate, so a batsman will not be out if the contact with the ball is inadvertent.\n\nThe only time a batsman has been dismissed obstructing the ball in a Test match was during the [[South African cricket team in England in 1951|South African cricket team's tour of England in 1951]] when, in the fifth Test, England's [[Leonard Hutton]] [[Glossary of cricket terms#T|top edged]] the ball and, thinking the ball would hit the stumps, attempted to hit the ball away, thereby preventing the [[wicket-keeper]] from [[Catch (cricket)|catching]] the ball.\n\n==Definition==\nObstructing the field is Law 37 in the [[Laws of cricket]] established by the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC). A batsman can be given out for obstructing the field if he wilfully attempts to obstruct or distract the fielding side by word or action.<ref name=\"mcc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.lords.org/mcc/laws-of-cricket/laws/law-37-obstructing-the-field/ |title=Law 37 \u2013 Obstructing the field |publisher=MCC |accessdate=29 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nLaw 37 describes the following three circumstances where this applies (but the law is not limited to these circumstances):\n*If, in the act of playing the ball, the batsmen wilfully strikes the ball with a hand not holding the bat, unless this is to avoid injury.{{efn|This situation was previously covered in a separate Law:[[Handled the ball]].}}\n\n*If either batsman should wilfully obstruct or distract a fielder preventing a catch being made.\n*If, at any time while the ball is in play and without the consent of a fielder, he uses his bat or any part of his person, to return the ball to any fielder.\nThe latter situation is rarely applied, as the fielding side generally accept that the batsman is being helpful in returning the ball. A bowler does not receive credit for the wicket when a batsman is dismissed in this fashion, and any runs that have been completed before the offence is committed are scored (unless the obstruction prevents a catch being made{{efn|In this case any penalty runs will stand.<ref name=\"mcc\"/>}}).\n\n==Earliest recorded instance==\nThe first known instance of a player being dismissed in a manner equivalent to the modern term 'Obstructing the field' occurred in a minor match at Sheffield on 27 August 1792, between [[Sheffield Cricket Club]] and Bents Green. The Bents Green player John Shaw, who scored 7 in the first innings, had his dismissal recorded as \"run out of the ground to hinder a catch\". The information was recorded by [[G. B. Buckley]] who found it in the ''Sheffield Advertiser'' dated 31 August 1792. Sheffield won by 10 wickets in a match that was notable for two other reasons, these being that it was the first match played in [[Yorkshire]] for which full scores are recorded and it was the earliest known instance of a three innings match.<ref>Buckley, pp.27\u201328.</ref>\n\n==Dismissals in international cricket==\n===Test cricket===\n[[Len Hutton]] is the only man given out this way in Test cricket, for an incident that occurred at [[The Oval]] during the [[South_African_cricket_team_in_England_in_1951#Fifth_Test|fifth Test]] of South Africa's tour of England in 1951.\n\n===One Day Internationals===\nIn [[One Day International]]s, [[Rameez Raja]] (for Pakistan against England at Karachi in 1987) was given out for hitting the ball away with his bat to avoid being run out going for his century off the last ball of the innings, and [[Mohinder Amarnath]] (for India against Sri Lanka at Ahmedabad in 1989) was given out for kicking the ball away to avoid being run out. Another batsman to be given out this way is [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] of [[Pakistan]] in the first ODI of [[India]] vs [[Pakistan]] Hutch Cup on 6 February 2006. After Inzamam drove the ball to mid off, Indian [[Suresh Raina]] threw it back to the striker's end, Inzamam stopping it with his bat. Umpire [[Simon Taufel]] gave him out as he was in the line of the stumps and out of his crease (and thus would have been run out had the ball hit the stumps).\n\n[[Mohammad Hafeez]] of Pakistan was dismissed obstructing the field on 21 March 2013 in the 4th ODI of the bilateral series match against South Africa. He became the first man to be given out obstructing the field after the new playing conditions were introduced.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/south-africa-v-pakistan-2013/engine/current/match/567371.html]</ref> His teammate, [[Anwar Ali (cricketer born 1987)|Anwar Ali]], was dismissed obstructing the field on 27 November 2013 in the second ODI against South Africa.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/south-africa-v-pakistan-2013-14/content/player/232491.html]</ref>\n\n[[Ben Stokes]] of England was dismissed obstructing the field on 5 September 2015 in the second ODI against Australia for stopping the ball with his hand when the bowler, Mitchell Starc, had thrown the ball in an attempt to run him out.<ref>http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283167.html</ref>\n\nThe complete list of batsmen given out obstructing the field in [[One Day International]]s is:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ One Day International dismissals obstructed the field\n|-\n! No\n! Batsman\n! Country\n! Opposition\n! Venue\n! Match\n! Date\n|-\n|| 1\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Rameez Raja]] \n|| {{cr|PAK}} || {{cr|ENG}} || [[National Stadium|Karachi]], [[Pakistan]] || [[English_cricket_team_in_Pakistan_in_1987\u201388#2nd_ODI|2nd ODI]] || 20 November 1987\n|-\n|| 2 \n! scope=\"row\" | [[Mohinder Amarnath]] \n|| {{cr|IND}} || {{cr|SRI}} || [[Sardar Patel Stadium|Ahmedabad]], [[India]] || [[Nehru Cup (cricket)#India vs Sri Lanka|ODI]] || 22 October 1989\n|-\n|| 3 \n! scope=\"row\" | [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] \n|| {{cr|PAK}} || {{cr|IND}} || [[Arbab Niaz Stadium|Peshawar]], [[Pakistan]] || [[Indian_cricket_team_in_Pakistan_in_2005\u201306#First_ODI|1st ODI]] || 6 February 2006\n|-\n|| 4 \n! scope=\"row\" | [[Mohammad Hafeez]] \n|| {{cr|PAK}} || {{cr|RSA}} || [[Kingsmead Cricket Ground|Durban]], South Africa || [[Pakistani_cricket_team_in_South_Africa_in_2012\u201313#4th_ODI|4th ODI]] || 21 March 2013\n|-\n||5\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Anwar Ali (cricketer born 1987)|Anwar Ali]]\n|| {{cr|PAK}} || {{cr|RSA}} || [[St George's Park Cricket Ground|Port Elizabeth]], South Africa || [[Pakistani_cricket_team_in_South_Africa_in_2013\u201314#2nd_ODI|2nd ODI]] || 27 November 2013\n|-\n||6\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Ben Stokes]]\n|| {{cr|ENG}} || {{cr|AUS}} || [[Lord's]], England || [[Australian_cricket_team_in_England_and_Ireland_in_2015#2nd_ODI|2nd ODI]] || 5 September 2015\n|-\n||7\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Xavier Marshall]]\n|| {{cr|USA}} || {{cr|UAE}} || [[Sharjah Cricket Stadium]], [[Sharjah]] || [[2019 United Arab Emirates Tri-Nation Series#1st_ODI|ODI]] || {{dts|format=dmy|2019|December|8}}\n|}\n\n===Women's One Day Internationals===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ Women's One Day International dismissals obstructed the field\n|-\n! No\n! Batswoman\n! Country\n! Opposition\n! Venue\n! Match\n! Date\n|-\n|| 1\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Thirush Kamini]]\n|| {{crw|IND}} || {{crw|WIN}} || [[ACA\u2013KDCA Cricket Ground|Vijayawada]], India || [[West_Indies_women%27s_cricket_team_in_India_in_2016\u201317#2nd_ODI|2nd ODI]] || 13 November 2016\n|}\n\n===T20 Internationals===\nOn 23 June 2017, in a Twenty20 match against South Africa, [[Jason Roy]] of England was given out obstructing the field, for changing the side of the pitch he was running on when returning from backing up. This caused the returned