et/14353907.stm, 31 July 2011</ref>\n\n[[Yusuf Pathan]] of India was dismissed obstructing the field on 15 May 2013 while playing for the Kolkata Knight Riders against the [[Pune Warriors India]] in Match 65 of the 2013 Indian Premier League for deliberately kicking the ball while rotating the strike. He became the first player to be dismissed in T20 cricket in this fashion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wisdenindia.com/cricket-news/yusuf-dismissal-divides-opinion/62480|title=Yusuf dismissal divides opinion|publisher=Wisden India|date=15 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Sheldon Jackson (cricketer)|Sheldon Jackson]] was given out obstructing the field on 3 March 2017 during the [[2016\u201317 Vijay Hazare Trophy]] match against [[Chhattisgarh cricket team|Chhattisgarh]]. Jackson became only the second Indian batsman to be given out in a [[List A cricket|List A match]] in this manner.<ref name=\"Jackson\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/vijay-hazare-trophy-2016-17/content/story/1085065.html |title=Jackson out obstructing the field in Saurashtra's win |accessdate=3 March 2017 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref>\n\n[[Alex Ross]] of the [[Brisbane Heat]] was given out obstructing the field in a [[2017-18 Big Bash League season|Big Bash League]] match against the [[Hobart Hurricanes]] in January 2018 for interfering with an attempted run out. It was the first time in Big Bash League history that a player was given out in this manner.<ref name=\"Ross\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22023835/twitter-reactions-very-very-embarrassing-absolutely-shocking |title='Very very embarrassing! Absolutely shocking'|accessdate=11 January 2018 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref>\n\n[[Ryan Burl]] was given out in a match in the [[2017\u201318 Logan Cup]] by obstructing the field, after he pushed the ball away from the stumps to protect his wicket.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.3-mob.com/sport/logan-cup-burl-hits-century-as-stars-clip-eagles/#.WtsfTH-fiUk |title=Logan Cup: Burl hits century as Stars clip Eagles |work=3-mob.com |accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of unusual dismissals in international cricket]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Buckley |first=G. B. |authorlink=G. B. Buckley |title=Fresh Light on pre-Victorian Cricket |year=1937 |publisher=Cotterell |isbn=}}\n* ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]'' \u2013 various issues\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130311210212/http://www.lords.org/laws-and-spirit/laws-of-cricket/laws/ The official laws of cricket]\n\n{{Methods of dismissal in cricket}}\n\n[[Category:Cricket laws and regulations]]\n[[Category:Cricket terminology]]\n", "name_user": "2405:6e00:a43:3000:f854:3bd6:7b07:9371", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDefinition)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obstructing_the_field"}
{"title_page": "Sanam Chandra Palace", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=February 2016}}\n[[Image:Chali Mongkol Asana.jpg|thumb|250px|Chali Mongkol Asana ({{Rtgs|''Chali Mongkhon At''}}), in the style of a European castle]]\n'''Sanam Chandra Palace''' ({{lang-th|\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e27\u0e31\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32\u0e21\u0e08\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e4c}}; {{Rtgs|''Sanam Chan''}}; \"Moon Plaza\") is a palace complex built by [[Vajiravudh]] in [[Nakhon Pathom Province]], [[Thailand]], 56&nbsp;km west of [[Bangkok]]. The palace complex is about a kilometer away from the [[Phra Pathommachedi]]. The complex consists of five buildings and a [[Ganesh]] shrine.\n\n==History==\n===Royal residence===\n[[File:0004933 SanamchandraPalace Ch.pongsakorn.jpg|thumb|In front of Sanam Chandra Palace]]\nBefore ascending the throne, the then [[Crown Prince]] [[Vajiravudh]] came to this city to pay homage to Phra Pathommachedi. He wished to build a palace here as a retreat and a residence during his pilgrimage trip to the stupa. He viewed the area as a strategic location. In 1907, he bought about 335 acres of land around Noen Prasart Hill ({{lang-th|\u0e40\u0e19\u0e34\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e17}}; {{Rtgs|''Noen Prasat''}}; \"Castle Hill\") from local people. Noen Prasart Hill is believed to be the site of an ancient palace. He then had Luang Phitak Manop (Noi Silapi, later Phraya Visukam Prasit) designed and supervised the construction of the palace. The construction began in 1902 by the end of [[Chulalongkorn]]'s reign (1868 \u2013 1910). It was completed in 1911. Vajiravudh named it Sanam Chandra Palace after a natural pool nearby called \"Sa Nam Chand\" ({{lang-th|\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e30\u0e19\u0e49\u0e33\u0e08\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e4c}}; {{Rtgs|''Sa Nam Chan''}}; \"Moon Pond\"). In addition, the king had another plan for this palace. It was to serve not only as a retreat, but also as a stronghold during a national crisis. Here, he regularly held practices for the [[Wild Tigers Corps]], a paramilitary troop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palaces.thai.net/day/index_sc.htm |title=Welcome to Sanam Chandra Palace |website=Palaces.thai.net |date= |accessdate=2016-02-05}}</ref> According to Vajiravudh's will, the palace was given to the government to be the site of [[Chulachomklao Royal Military Academy|military academy]]. However, after reign of Vajiravudh the palace has been closed and transformed to [[Nakhon Pathom]]'s administrative area. Some palace halls had been dismantled and moved to National Museum in Bangkok for preservation.\n\n===Silpakorn University Campus===\nIn 1965 [[Silpakorn University]], a well known Thai university, for art and archaeology study, improved its educational program with additional new faculties and urgently need larger area to accommodate the expansion. The university and Thai cabinet approved to use the area of Sanam Chandra Palace to be the new university campus since the area was suitable since the palace was once belong to [[Vajiravudh]], an archeologist and artist himself. Also in the palace ground has [[Ganesh]] Shrine, god of art and the symbol of university seal. Moreover, [[Nakhon Pathom]] is an important archaeological site for [[Dvaravati]] in Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.su.ac.th/html_about/about_location_sanamchandra02.asp |accessdate=July 5, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080125133641/http://www.su.ac.th/html_about/about_location_sanamchandra02.asp |archivedate=January 25, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Restoration===\nIn 1981 [[Department of Fine Arts (Thailand)|Department of Fine Arts]] registered Sanam Chandra Palace as historical site. On December 1 st, 2003, the Committee for the Renovation of Sanam Chandra Palace chaired by Prince. [[Bejaratana Rajasuda]], [[Vajiravudh]]'s daughter, in collaboration with the Ministry of Interior, Nakhon Pathom Governor and [[Silpakorn University]] returned the palace including its satellite buildings to [[Bureau of the Royal Household]] following the wishes of Bejaratana Rajasuda. At present, the Bureau of the Royal Household has since opened the Bhimarn Prathom Residence including the Prayer Room in this residence, Samakkeemukamartaya Hall, Ganesh Shrine, Chaleemongkolasana Residence, Mareerajaratanabulung Residence, Thub Kwan Residence and Statue of Yalae, to the general public.\n\nSanam Chandra Palace celebrated its 100-year anniversary from November 23, 2007 to December 2, 2007.\n\n===Temporary Closing===\nFrom October 1 st, 2017, Sanam Chandra Palace is temporary closing for renovation. The reopening date is still unannounced <ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.kapook.com/view180132.html|accessdate=December 17, 2017  |title=\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e27\u0e31\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32\u0e21\u0e08\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e4c \u0e19\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e16\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e38\u0e07\u0e22\u0e32\u0e27 \u0e40\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48\u0e22\u0e27\u0e0a\u0e21\u0e27\u0e31\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e17\u0e49\u0e32\u0e22 30 \u0e01.\u0e22. \u0e19\u0e35\u0e49 |date=2017-09-26 }}</ref>.\n\n==Buildings==\n===Bhimarn Prathom Residence===\nThe first hall to be built in this palace, the '''Bhimarn Prathom Residence''' ({{Lang-th|\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e21\u0e32\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e10\u0e21}}; {{Rtgs|''Phiman Pathom''}}) is a brick-and-cement building in western style, which was adapted to suit the tropical climate. The ventilation panes and railings around the upper floor of the building are in traditional elaborate Thai carving patterns. Located upstairs are a bed chamber, a bathroom, a dressing room, a conference room, a dining room, and a prayer room. In the prayer room sits a Buddha image in the First Sermon Attitude. The exquisite angelic congregation design on the mural in the prayer room was painted by Phraya Anusart Jitrakorn (Chan Jitrakorn).\n\nThe residence frequently served as H. M. King Rama VI \u2018 s private quarters (particularly before his [[Coronation of the Thai monarch|coronation]], and afterwards until 1913), his study, a reception hall, and an audience hall.\n\n===Samakkeemukamartaya Hall===\nThe '''Samakkeemukkamartaya Hall''' ({{Lang-th|\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e21\u0e31\u0e04\u0e04\u0e35\u0e21\u0e38\u0e02\u0e21\u0e32\u0e15\u0e22\u0e4c}}; {{Rtgs|''Samakkhi Mukkha Mat''}})\n\n===Chaleemongkolasana Residence===\nThe '''Charliemongkolasana''' Residence is located in Sanamchandra Palace, Nakhonpathom. In 1908, this residence was built in the integration of 2 arts which are French renaissance and English half-timber. This residence was adapted for Thai weather atmosphere. At that time, the residence was named \u201cYah Leh Residence\u201d which came from the name of King Rama 6 (King Vajiravudh)\u2019s dog.\n\nIn 1915, King Rama 6 gave the name for this residence which is Charliemongkolasana residence that means \u201cthe auspicious residence of Charlie\u201d. This residence was used for the residence of King Rama 6 when he met the Wild Tiger Corps at Sanamchandra Palace.\nThe residence looks like a reddish-yellow small castle which has 2 floors and red roof-tile. The dining room and the living room are on the first floor. The study room, the royal bathroom and the royal bed chamber are on the second floor. The Yah Leh monument is located in front of this residence. There is a bridge that links between the Charliemongkolasana Residence and the Maleeratanabanlang Residence (Thai style residence). These two residences are the combination of Thai and Western arts.\n<ref>Chaleemongkolasana Residence.  October 25, 2017. From http://www.palaces.thai.net/day/new/sc/chalee.htm</ref>\n<ref>Jitprapai Leewitaryar.  chaleemaree. October 25, 2017.  From http://chaleemaree.blogspot.com/</ref>\n<ref>\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e15\u0e33\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35\u0e21\u0e07\u0e04\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e4c.  October 25, 2017.  From [[:th:\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e15\u0e33\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35\u0e21\u0e07\u0e04\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e4c|\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e15\u0e33\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35\u0e21\u0e07\u0e04\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e4c]]</ref>\n\n===Mareerajaratanabulung Residence===\nThe '''Mareerajaratanabulung Residence''' ({{Lang-th|\u0e21\u0e32\u0e23\u0e35\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e23\u0e31\u0e15\u0e1a\u0e31\u0e25\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07\u0e01\u0e4c}}; {{Rtgs|''Mari Ratcha Rat Banlang''}})\n\n===Thub Kwan Residence===\nThe '''Thub Kwan Residence''' ({{Lang-th|\u0e17\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e02\u0e27\u0e31\u0e0d}}; {{Rtgs|''Thap Khwan''}})\n\n===Ganesh Shrine===\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nimage:Ganesh_memorial,_Sanam_Chan_palace,_Thailand.jpg|Ganesh memorial, with Phra Pathom Chedi in the background\nImage:Yalae Rama VI's beloved dog.jpg|Statue of Yah Leh, beloved dog of King Rama VI\nImage:Phiman Pathom.jpg|Phiman Pathom Residence\nImage:Samakkhi Mukamat.jpg|Vajariromaya Residence \nImage:Thap Khwan.jpg|Thap Khwan Residence\nImage:Chali_Mongkol_Asana_rear_side.jpg| Chali Mongkol Asana's rear side\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: Image:Mareerajaratabulung Residence.jpg| Mareerajaratabulung Residence  -->\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sanam Chan Palace}}\n*[http://www.vimanmek.com/exhibit/sanamchandra.php Sanam Chandra Palace]\n\n{{Royal palaces in Thailand}}\n\n{{coord|13|49|10|N|100|2|43|E|type:landmark_region:TH|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Nakhon Pathom Province]]\n[[Category:Former royal residences in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Nakhon Pathom Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=February 2016}}\n[[Image:Chali Mongkol Asana.jpg|thumb|250px|Chali Mongkol Asana ({{Rtgs|''Chali Mongkhon At''}}), in the style of a European castle]]\n'''Sanam Chandra Palace''' ({{lang-th|\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e27\u0e31\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32\u0e21\u0e08\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e4c}}; {{Rtgs|''Sanam Chan''}}; \"Moon Plaza\") is a palace complex built by [[Vajiravudh]] in [[Nakhon Pathom Province]], [[Thailand]], 56&nbsp;km west of [[Bangkok]]. The palace complex is about a kilometer away from the [[Phra Pathommachedi]]. The complex consists of five buildings and a [[Ganesh]] shrine.\n\n==History==\n===Royal residence===\n[[File:0004933 SanamchandraPalace Ch.pongsakorn.jpg|thumb|In front of Sanam Chandra Palace]]\nBefore ascending the throne, the then [[Crown Prince]] [[Vajiravudh]] came to this city to pay homage to Phra Pathommachedi. He wished to build a palace here as a retreat and a residence during his pilgrimage trip to the stupa. He viewed the area as a strategic location. In 1907, he bought about 335 acres of land around Noen Prasart Hill ({{lang-th|\u0e40\u0e19\u0e34\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e17}}; {{Rtgs|''Noen Prasat''}}; \"Castle Hill\") from local people. Noen Prasart Hill is believed to be the site of an ancient palace. He then had Luang Phitak Manop (Noi Silapi, later Phraya Visukam Prasit) designed and supervised the construction of the palace. The construction began in 1902 by the end of [[Chulalongkorn]]'s reign (1868 \u2013 1910). It was completed in 1911. Vajiravudh named it Sanam Chandra Palace after a natural pool nearby called \"Sa Nam Chand\" ({{lang-th|\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e30\u0e19\u0e49\u0e33\u0e08\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e4c}}; {{Rtgs|''Sa Nam Chan''}}; \"Moon Pond\"). In addition, the king had another plan for this palace. It was to serve not only as a retreat, but also as a stronghold during a national crisis. Here, he regularly held practices for the [[Wild Tigers Corps]], a paramilitary troop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palaces.thai.net/day/index_sc.htm |title=Welcome to Sanam Chandra Palace |website=Palaces.thai.net |date= |accessdate=2016-02-05}}</ref> According to Vajiravudh's will, the palace was given to the government to be the site of [[Chulachomklao Royal Military Academy|military academy]]. However, after reign of Vajiravudh the palace has been closed and transformed to [[Nakhon Pathom]]'s administrative area. Some palace halls had been dismantled and moved to National Museum in Bangkok for preservation.\n\n===Silpakorn University Campus===\nIn 1965 [[Silpakorn University]], a well known Thai university, for art and archaeology study, improved its educational program with additional new faculties and urgently need larger area to accommodate the expansion. The university and Thai cabinet approved to use the area of Sanam Chandra Palace to be the new university campus since the area was suitable since the palace was once belong to [[Vajiravudh]], an archeologist and artist himself. Also in the palace ground has [[Ganesh]] Shrine, god of art and the symbol of university seal. Moreover, [[Nakhon Pathom]] is an important archaeological site for [[Dvaravati]] in Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.su.ac.th/html_about/about_location_sanamchandra02.asp |accessdate=July 5, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080125133641/http://www.su.ac.th/html_about/about_location_sanamchandra02.asp |archivedate=January 25, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Restoration===\nIn 1981 [[Department of Fine Arts (Thailand)|Department of Fine Arts]] registered Sanam Chandra Palace as historical site. On December 1 st, 2003, the Committee for the Renovation of Sanam Chandra Palace chaired by [[Bejaratana Rajasuda]], [[Vajiravudh]]'s daughter, in collaboration with the Ministry of Interior, Nakhon Pathom Governor and [[Silpakorn University]] returned the palace including its satellite buildings to Bureau of the Royal Household following the wishes of [[Bejaratana Rajasuda]]. At present, the Bureau of the Royal Household has since opened the Bhimarn Prathom Residence including the Prayer Room in this residence, Samakkeemukamartaya Hall, Ganesh Shrine, Chaleemongkolasana Residence, Mareerajaratanabulung Residence, Thub Kwan Residence and Statue of Yalae, to the general public.\n\nSanam Chandra Palace celebrated its 100-year anniversary from November 23, 2007 to December 2, 2007.\n\n===Temporary Closing===\nFrom October 1 st, 2017, Sanam Chandra Palace is temporary closing for renovation. The reopening date is still unannounced <ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.kapook.com/view180132.html|accessdate=December 17, 2017  |title=\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e27\u0e31\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e32\u0e21\u0e08\u0e31\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e4c \u0e19\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e16\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e38\u0e07\u0e22\u0e32\u0e27 \u0e40\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48\u0e22\u0e27\u0e0a\u0e21\u0e27\u0e31\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e17\u0e49\u0e32\u0e22 30 \u0e01.\u0e22. \u0e19\u0e35\u0e49 |date=2017-09-26 }}</ref>.\n\n==Buildings==\n===Bhimarn Prathom Residence===\nThe first hall to be built in this palace, the '''Bhimarn Prathom Residence''' ({{Lang-th|\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e21\u0e32\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e10\u0e21}}; {{Rtgs|''Phiman Pathom''}}) is a brick-and-cement building in western style, which was adapted to suit the tropical climate. The ventilation panes and railings around the upper floor of the building are in traditional elaborate Thai carving patterns. Located upstairs are a bed chamber, a bathroom, a dressing room, a conference room, a dining room, and a prayer room. In the prayer room sits a Buddha image in the First Sermon Attitude. The exquisite angelic congregation design on the mural in the prayer room was painted by Phraya Anusart Jitrakorn (Chan Jitrakorn).\n\nThe residence frequently served as H. M. King Rama VI \u2018 s private quarters (particularly before his [[Coronation of the Thai monarch|coronation]], and afterwards until 1913), his study, a reception hall, and an audience hall.\n\n===Samakkeemukamartaya Hall===\nThe '''Samakkeemukkamartaya Hall''' ({{Lang-th|\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e21\u0e31\u0e04\u0e04\u0e35\u0e21\u0e38\u0e02\u0e21\u0e32\u0e15\u0e22\u0e4c}}; {{Rtgs|''Samakkhi Mukkha Mat''}})\n\n===Chaleemongkolasana Residence===\nThe '''Charliemongkolasana''' Residence is located in Sanamchandra Palace, Nakhonpathom. In 1908, this residence was built in the integration of 2 arts which are French renaissance and English half-timber. This residence was adapted for Thai weather atmosphere. At that time, the residence was named \u201cYah Leh Residence\u201d which came from the name of King Rama 6 (King Vajiravudh)\u2019s dog.\n\nIn 1915, King Rama 6 gave the name for this residence which is Charliemongkolasana residence that means \u201cthe auspicious residence of Charlie\u201d. This residence was used for the residence of King Rama 6 when he met the Wild Tiger Corps at Sanamchandra Palace.\nThe residence looks like a reddish-yellow small castle which has 2 floors and red roof-tile. The dining room and the living room are on the first floor. The study room, the royal bathroom and the royal bed chamber are on the second floor. The Yah Leh monument is located in front of this residence. There is a bridge that links between the Charliemongkolasana Residence and the Maleeratanabanlang Residence (Thai style residence). These two residences are the combination of Thai and Western arts.\n<ref>Chaleemongkolasana Residence.  October 25, 2017. From http://www.palaces.thai.net/day/new/sc/chalee.htm</ref>\n<ref>Jitprapai Leewitaryar.  chaleemaree. October 25, 2017.  From http://chaleemaree.blogspot.com/</ref>\n<ref>\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e15\u0e33\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35\u0e21\u0e07\u0e04\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e4c.  October 25, 2017.  From [[:th:\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e15\u0e33\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35\u0e21\u0e07\u0e04\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e4c|\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e15\u0e33\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35\u0e21\u0e07\u0e04\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e19\u0e4c]]</ref>\n\n===Mareerajaratanabulung Residence===\nThe '''Mareerajaratanabulung Residence''' ({{Lang-th|\u0e21\u0e32\u0e23\u0e35\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e23\u0e31\u0e15\u0e1a\u0e31\u0e25\u0e25\u0e31\u0e07\u0e01\u0e4c}}; {{Rtgs|''Mari Ratcha Rat Banlang''}})\n\n===Thub Kwan Residence===\nThe '''Thub Kwan Residence''' ({{Lang-th|\u0e17\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e02\u0e27\u0e31\u0e0d}}; {{Rtgs|''Thap Khwan''}})\n\n===Ganesh Shrine===\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nimage:Ganesh_memorial,_Sanam_Chan_palace,_Thailand.jpg|Ganesh memorial, with Phra Pathom Chedi in the background\nImage:Yalae Rama VI's beloved dog.jpg|Statue of Yah Leh, beloved dog of King Rama VI\nImage:Phiman Pathom.jpg|Phiman Pathom Residence\nImage:Samakkhi Mukamat.jpg|Vajariromaya Residence \nImage:Thap Khwan.jpg|Thap Khwan Residence\nImage:Chali_Mongkol_Asana_rear_side.jpg| Chali Mongkol Asana's rear side\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: Image:Mareerajaratabulung Residence.jpg| Mareerajaratabulung Residence  -->\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sanam Chan Palace}}\n*[http://www.vimanmek.com/exhibit/sanamchandra.php Sanam Chandra Palace]\n\n{{Royal palaces in Thailand}}\n\n{{coord|13|49|10|N|100|2|43|E|type:landmark_region:TH|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Nakhon Pathom Province]]\n[[Category:Former royal residences in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Nakhon Pathom Province]]\n", "name_user": "Sodacan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanam_Chandra_Palace"}
